Klaus reveals who and what he is to Cami in order to get her on his side. One of the witches, Agnes, sends Hayley to a doctor, which is all a trap. The witch sends some men to go after Hayley (and possibly kill her and the baby), but Hayley is able to escape. When Hayley protects herself against some of the men, Rebekah comes in to save her but both of them get shot with an arrow. Rebekah, who thinks that Marcel will not give Elijah back decides to do a research and find him by herself. When she goes to the church, Rebekah finds the place where Marcel and Davina hold Elijah. Davina who finally got out, went to see the boy she liked from school, Tim. When Klaus plays mind games with her, he pushes Tim and leaves Davina to make a choice if she needs him alive or not. Klaus saves the boy and leaves Davina confused whether she could trust Marcel or not. When Klaus comes to look for Hayley, she shows up and tells him and Rebekah that a wolf saved her. Elijah arrives and tells Davina it's time for them to talk.

title: Monument to the 60th French Infantry Regiment at Ville-en-Tardenois
table-1240-919.pgTitle: List of World War I memorials and cemeteries in Champagne-Ardennes
table-1240-919.secondTitle: Monument to the 60th French Infantry Regiment at Ville-en-Tardenois
table-1240-919.caption: The Ferme de Navarin Monument
data: This monument stands on the RD 980 as one leaves Ville-en-Tardenois in the direction of Dormans and south-west of Reims. The inscription reminds us that many men of the 60th French Infantry Regiment fell fighting in the woods of Courmont, Bonval and Cohette and the area around Ville-en-Tardenois in the attacks against the Germans from 26 July to 2 August 1918.

table-1240-934.caption: Monuments to the 24th, 28th, 133rd and 363th French Infantry Regiments at Loivre
data: The monument to the 132nd and 332nd French Infantry Regiment plus the 46th Territorials features a sculpture of a French soldier (poilu) and it was part of the scheme to reconstruct Reims after the war initiated by the architects Hippolyte Portevin and Max Sainsaulieu. The actual monument was the design of the architect Émile Fanjat and was funded by subscriptions raised by the veterans of the 132nd in particular to honour the men who were killed fighting in the Éparges between 23 October 1914 and 12 April 1915. The inscription on the monument reads "Aux morts des 132e et 332e Régiments d'infanterie et du 46e Régiment territorial d'infanterie" The soldier on the top of the monument is the work of Paul Lefèbvre who worked on the Reims monument aux morts.

title: The Fort de la Pompelle and the defence of Reims
table-1240-913.pgTitle: List of World War I memorials and cemeteries in Champagne-Ardennes
table-1240-913.secondTitle: The Fort de la Pompelle and the defence of Reims
table-1240-913.caption: French Military Cemetery at Sommepy-Tahure
data: The Fort of la Pompelle played a vital role in the defence of Reims throughout the war and early in 1918 the Germans attacked the fort in great strength in an effort to capture it. The German's failed, with the 6th Company of the 21st Colonial Infantry Regiment carrying out a successful defence. On 15 July 1918, Ludendorf launched the last German offensive along the Champagne front and the 7th Colonial Infantry Regiment, who at that time were defending the fort, fought off an attack which was to be the last against the fort. Nevertheless until 5 October 1918, when the Germans evacuated their positions in front of Reims, the fort was still subjected to frequent artillery bombardments. The organisation "Souvenir Français" organised a memorial at the "Ferme d’Alger" inscribed "Aux héros de la Grande Guerre", 4 kilomètres from Reims on the Route Nationale 44, direction Châlons-sur-Marne, as this was where most of the fighting took place to defend the Fort de la Pompelle. The monument was restored in 1998 on the 80th anniversary of the 1918 armistice and carries the inscription "En mémoire des soldats tombés héroïquement pour la défense du secteur Septembre 1914-Octobre 1918"
